&lt;/ul&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] C++ std::domain_error — Mathematical Domain Error Fix</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/cpp/domainerror/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/cpp/domainerror/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="solution-c-stddomain_error--mathematical-domain-error-fix"&gt;[Solution] C++ std::domain_error — Mathematical Domain Error Fix&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;code&gt;std::domain_error&lt;/code&gt; is thrown when a function receives an argument that is outside its mathematical domain — meaning the operation is not defined for that input. Common examples include taking the square root of a negative number, computing the logarithm of a non-positive number, or using inverse trigonometric functions outside their valid range.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="why-stddomain_error-occurs"&gt;Why std::domain_error Occurs&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Common causes include computing &lt;code&gt;sqrt()&lt;/code&gt; of a negative number, computing &lt;code&gt;log()&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;log10()&lt;/code&gt; of zero or negative values, using &lt;code&gt;asin()&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;acos()&lt;/code&gt; with values outside [-1, 1], and performing mathematical operations where the result would be undefined.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>